ğŸ“˜ Day 1 Notes (Java AI) â€” CSV Loading + DataFrame
ğŸ¯ Goal of Day 1

To build the first step of any AI project:

âœ… Load a dataset (CSV) into Java
âœ… Convert it into a structure we can process (DataFrame)
âœ… Preview the data to verify itâ€™s correct

ğŸ§  What is Machine Learning?

Machine Learning is:

Training a program to learn patterns from data instead of writing rules manually.

Funny example ğŸ˜„

A spam filter made with rules is like:

â€œIf message contains FREE â†’ spamâ€

â€œIf message contains WIN â†’ spamâ€

But spammers change spelling.
ML is like a smart bouncer who learns from many spam examples.

ğŸ“Œ Why We Start With CSV?

Because most ML datasets are stored as:

CSV files

Excel files

Database tables

CSV is the simplest format to begin.

ğŸ§¾ What is a DataFrame?

A DataFrame is like an Excel table:

Rows = records (examples)

Columns = features (inputs)

Example:

age	study_hours	marks
20	2	45

In ML:

age, study_hours â†’ input features

marks â†’ target (output)

ğŸ§© What Our Java Code Does
Step 1 â€” Find the CSV inside resources

We use:

getClassLoader().getResource("data/students.csv")


âœ… This is the correct professional way because it works even when:

running from IntelliJ

running from a JAR

deploying to a server

Step 2 â€” Convert URL â†’ Path (Windows safe)

We do:

Paths.get(resource.toURI())


âœ… This avoids Windows path issues (\ backslashes).

Step 3 â€” Load CSV into DataFrame

We do:

DataFrame df = Read.csv(path);


Now the dataset is ready for:

cleaning

preprocessing

ML model training

Step 4 â€” Print dataset summary

We check:

df.nrows() â†’ how many rows

df.ncols() â†’ how many columns

This is important because ML models need enough data.

Step 5 â€” Preview the data

We print a slice:

df.slice(0, 6)


This is like checking the first few rows in Excel.

âœ… Corrections / Important Notes
âœ… Correction 1: Smile version mismatch

Your system is currently using:

Smile 2.6.0

So some methods (like Read.csv(InputStream)) donâ€™t exist.

Thatâ€™s why we used:
âœ… Read.csv(Path)

âœ… Correction 2: Header row issue

Your CSV has a header:

name,age,study_hours,marks


But Smile 2.6.0 reads it like normal data.

Thatâ€™s why you saw the header inside rows.

Fix options:

âœ… Option A (simple for beginners): Remove header row
âœ… Option B (later): Use a better CSV reader configuration

For now we will use Option A.

âœ… Correction 3: SLF4J warning

This warning:

SLF4J: Failed to load class "org.slf4j.impl.StaticLoggerBinder"


Is not an error.

It just means Smile wanted logging, but no logger implementation is added.

We will fix it later when needed.

